fields.iResourceAbstract: Down-welling Surface Short-wave Flux (DSSF) is defined as the radiative energy reaching the Earth's surface in the wavelength interval [0.3µm, 4.0µm] per time and surface unit. It essentially depends on the solar zenith angle, on cloud coverage,  and to a lesser extent on atmospheric absorption and surface albedo. DSSF fields are crucial for a wide number of applications involving scientific domains like weather forecast, hydrology, climate, agriculture and environment-related studies. In numerical weather prediction and general circulation models of the atmosphere, satellite-derived DSSF estimates can either be used as a control variable or as a substitute to validation data from surface radiation measurement networks.
fields.series_title: Global Down-welling Surface Short-wave Flux 2009-2012 Series
fields.lineage: The method for the retrieval of DSSF that is implemented in the Geoland-2 system largely follows that of LSA SAF and previous developments achieved at Météo-France in the framework of the SAF on Ocean & Sea-Ice. Separate algorithms are applied for clear sky and cloudy sky situations. In the presence of clouds the down-welling radiation reaching the ground is considerably reduced, and DSSF is strongly anti-correlated with the observed top-of-atmosphere reflectances: the brighter the clouds appear on the satellite images, the more radiation is reflected by them and the less reaches the surface. In this case, the estimation of DSSF makes use of TOA reflectances in the visible and near-infrared channels, which are converted into broad-band TOA albedo. This then serves as the most important input information for a physical parameterisation of the atmospheric radiation transfer in cloudy conditions. In the clear sky method DSSF is directly determined with an empirical parameterisation for the effective transmittance of the atmosphere as a function of the concentration of atmospheric constituents. For more detailed information consult the Product User Manual.
fields.iCredit: The research leading to these results has received funding from the European Community’s Seventh Framework Program (FP7/2007-2013) under grant agreement n°218795. The DSSF product is the property of the Institute of Meteorology of Portugal under copyright geoland2. It is generated from the MTSAT, GOES and MSG data provided by Eumetsat. The BioPar DSSF is available at the address http://www.geoland2.eu

fields.iResourceAbstract: Down-welling Surface Long-wave Flux (DSLF) is defined as the irradiance reaching the surface in the thermal infrared part of the spectrum (4-100 µm). It is essentially determined by low level atmospheric temperature, water vapour and clouds. DSLF fields are crucial for a wide number of applications involving scientific domains like weather forecast, hydrology, climate, agriculture and environment-related studies. In numerical weather prediction and general circulation models of the atmosphere, satellite-derived DSLF estimates can either be used as a control variable or as a substitute to validation data from surface radiation measurement networks.
fields.series_title: Global Down-welling Surface Long-wave Flux 2009-2012 Series
fields.lineage: The methodology used for DSLF estimations within Geoland-2 combines the signature of clouds on infrared and visible channels with information on atmosphere water vapour content and near surface temperature from Numerical Weather Prediction (NWP) models. This is based on the assumption that the latter, which also include the assimilation of measurements from sounding instruments along with other remotely sensed and conventional observations, provide the best knowledge of atmospheric profiles at any given point. For more detailed information consult the Product User Manual.
fields.iCredit: The research leading to these results has received funding from the European Community’s Seventh Framework Program (FP7/2007-2013) under grant agreement n°218795. The DSLF product is the property of the Institute of Meteorology of Portugal under copyright geoland2. It is generated from the MTSAT, GOES and MSG data provided by Eumetsat. The BioPar DSLF is available at the address http://www.geoland2.eu

fields.iResourceAbstract: Land Surface Temperature (LST) is the radiative skin temperature over land. LST plays an important role in the physics of land surface as it is involved in the processes of energy and water exchange with the atmosphere. LST is useful for the scientific community, namely for those dealing with meteorological and climate models. Accurate values of LST are also of special interest in a wide range of areas related to land surface processes, including meteorology, hydrology, agrometeorology, climatology and environmental studies.
fields.lineage: The objective of the LST product developed within the framework of Geoland-2 is to increase the area coverage of the LST product currently distributed by the Eumetsat Satellite Application Facility (SAF) on Land Surface Analysis (LSA). The LSA SAF generates, archives and disseminates LST from SEVIRI (onboard MSG) with a 15-minute frequency, at the original satellite spatial resolution. A near global product is obtained by merging SEVIRI- with GOES- and MTSAT-based LST produced with an hourly frequency. The Geoland-2 team benefits from the experience gained during the development of the LSA SAF LST product for the design and implementation of GOES and MTSAT LST algorithms. For more detailed information consult the Product User Manual.
fields.iCredit: The research leading to these results has received funding from the European Community’s Seventh Framework Program (FP7/2007-2013) under grant agreement n°218795. The LST product is the property of the Institute of Meteorology of Portugal under copyright geoland2. It is generated from the MTSAT, GOES and MSG data provided by Eumetsat. The BioPar LST is available at the address http://www.geoland2.eu
